      "content": "The economic case for strict enforcement rests on the concept of labor market saturation and the strain on public infrastructure. When immigration is uncontrolled, an influx of low-skilled labor can depress wages for native-born workers in those same sectors, as employers can rely on a cheaper, easily accessible workforce. Moreover, an unmanaged flow places significant, immediate burdens on local public resources like schools, healthcare, and social services, which are funded by taxpayers.",
      "source": "target",
